\begin_layout Itemize
A 95% Confidence Interval would have 2 meanings
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
1.
 Repeated Sampling: 95% of sample estimates would fall into 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{\theta}_{low},\,\hat{\theta}_{high}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2.
 Degree of Belief: The probability is 0.95 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{\theta}_{low},\hat{\,\theta}_{high}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout BeginFrame
CI: The First Interpretation: Repeated Sampling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you knew the sampling distribution, you could get a math genius to figure
 out the range.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Prob(\widehat{\theta_{low}}<\widehat{\theta}<\widehat{\theta_{high}})\label{eq:-7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This pre-supposes you know the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the PDF of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 (And that you know a math genius.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
One custom is to pick the low and high edges so that
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Prob(\widehat{\theta_{low}}<\widehat{\theta}<\widehat{\theta_{high}})=0.95\label{eq:-8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we repeated this experiment over and over, then the probability that
 the estimate will be between 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\theta_{low}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\theta_{high}}$
\end_inset

 is 0.95.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Repeat: There is a 95% chance that a random sample estimate will lie between
 the two edges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

p-value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

