\begin_layout Subsection
Student's T Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The Sampling Distribution of the Mean/Std.Err.(Mean) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Previous supposed I knew 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now I make the problem more challenging, forcing myself to estimate the
 mean, and standard error of the mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the end, we NEVER create a sampling distribution for the mean by itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We DO estimate the sampling distribution of the ratio of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

estimation mean
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}-\mu$
\end_inset

) to its standard error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Intuition: The CI will be symmetric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}\pm something$
\end_inset

, using the sampling distribution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Sample Mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Collect some observations, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sample mean (call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

) is an estimate of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expected value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
sample\, mean\, of\, x:\bar{x}=\hat{\mu}=\frac{1}{N}\sum x_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The mean is an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unbiased
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimator, meaning its expected value is equal to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the expected value
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[\bar{x}]\equiv E[\hat{\mu}]=E[x_{i}]=\mu
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\sim N(\mu,\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset

, the experts tell us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 (or
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

) is Normally distributed 
\begin_inset Formula $Normal(\mu,\frac{1}{N}\sigma^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall the CLT as a way to generalize this finding: the sampling distribution
 of the mean is Normal
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Estimate the Parameter Sigma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Sample Variance is the mean of squared errors
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
sample\, variance(x_{i})=\frac{\sum(x_{i}-\bar{x})^{2}}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

N-1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem comes in.
 This sample variance is not an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unbiased
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 I mean, sadly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[sample\, variance(x_{i})]\neq\sigma^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, a corrected estimator 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
unbiased\, sample\, variance(x_{i})=\frac{\sum(x_{i}-\bar{x})^{2}}{N-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is unbiased:
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[unbiased\, sample\, variance(x_{i})]=\sigma^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Standard Error of the Mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two lectures ago, I showed that the variance of the mean is proportional
 to the true variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var[\hat{\mu}]\, same\, as\, Var[\bar{x}]=\frac{1}{N}Var[x_{i}]=\frac{1}{N}\sigma^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(no matter what the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 might be).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We don't know the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variance 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[x_{i}]=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, but we can take the unbiased sample estimator and use it place of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That gives us the dreaded double hatted estimate of the estimated mean:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{Var[\hat{\mu]}}=\frac{1}{N}unbiased\, sample\, variance(x_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plug in
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $unbiased\, sample\, variance\, of\, x_{i}$
\end_inset

 from the previous page if you want to write out a formula!
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The magical ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $std.err.(\hat{\mu})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because the double hat notation is boring, we call the square root of it
 the standard error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
std.err.(\bar{x})\, same\, as\, std.err.(\hat{\mu})=\sqrt{\widehat{Var[\hat{\mu]}}}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}unbiased\, sample\, variance(x_{i})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall the definition of the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard error.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It is an estimate of the standard deviation of a sampling distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Gosset showed that although the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is unknown, the ratio of the estimated mean's fluctuations about its true
 value to the estimated standard deviation of the mean follows a T distribution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\hat{\mu}-\mu}{\widehat{std.dev.(\hat{\mu})}}=\frac{\hat{\mu}-\mu}{std.err.(\hat{\mu})}\sim T(\nu=N-1)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This new 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

t variable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 becomes our primary interest.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[x]$
\end_inset

 is unknowable, we have to learn to live with the estimate of it, and that
 brings us down a chain to T.
\end_layout

