\begin_layout BeginFrame
Proportions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Normal approximation is widely used, but...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Its valid when 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is more than 100 or so and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mid ranges
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Normal approximation lets us take this general idea: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CI=[\hat{\pi}-something\, low,\,\,\hat{\pi}+something\, high]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
and replace it with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CI=[\hat{\pi}-1.96\cdot std.error.(\hat{\pi}),\hat{\pi}+1.96\cdot std.error(\hat{\pi})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Show My Work: Derive the std.error(
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

)? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a Sidenote.
 Start with the Expected Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall, for any random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[x]=\sum prob(x)*x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The chance of a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and the chance of a 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\pi)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E[x] & = & \pi*1+(1-\pi)*0\nonumber \\
 & = & \pi\label{eq:-4}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Show My Work: For the Binomial Case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The observations are 1's and 0's representing successes and failures: 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1,0,1,1,0,1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The estimated mean is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

successful
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 proportion of observed scores
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\pi}=\frac{\sum x_{i}}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall this is always true for means, the expected value of the estimate
 the mean is the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[\hat{\pi}]=\pi\label{eq:-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So it makes sense that we act as though 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is in the center of the CI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Show My Work: 
\begin_inset Formula $E[\hat{\pi}]=E[x]=\pi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This uses the simple fact that expected value is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

linear operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $E[a\cdot x_{1}+bx_{2}]=aE[x_{1}]+bE[x_{2}]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Begin with the definition of the estimated mean:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\pi}=\frac{x_{1}}{N}+\frac{x_{2}}{N}+\ldots+\frac{x_{N}}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[\hat{\pi}]=E\left[\frac{x_{1}}{N}\right]+\left[\frac{x_{2}}{N}\right]+\ldots+\left[\frac{x_{N}}{N}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E[\hat{\pi}]=N\cdot\frac{E[x]}{N}=E[x]=\pi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Show My Work: Variance is Easy Too
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Recall the variance is a probability weighted sum of squared deviations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var[x]=\sum prob(x)*x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For one draw, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Var[x]= &  & \pi*(1-\pi)^{2}+(1-\pi)(0-\pi)^{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & (1-\pi)(\pi*(1-\pi)+\pi^{2})\nonumber \\
 & = & \pi(1-\pi)\label{eq:-5}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And if we draw N times and calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}=\sum x/N$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var[\hat{\pi}]=\frac{Var[x]}{N}=\frac{\pi(1-\pi)}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that's the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, AKA the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theoretical variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Show My Work: Here's where we get the standard error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}$
\end_inset

 is the square root of the variance 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
std.dev.(\hat{\pi})=\sqrt{Var[\hat{\pi}]}=\frac{\sqrt{\pi(1-\pi)}}{\sqrt{N}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true standard deviation.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As we saw in the CLT lecture, the dispersion of the estimator 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

collapses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rapidly as the sample increases because it is the variance divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We don't know 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, however.
 So from the sample, we estimate it by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 (or, we could call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use that estimate in place of the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and the value is called the standard error 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
std.error(\hat{\pi})=\sqrt{\pi(1-\pi)}/\sqrt{N}
\]

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

